












Project Analysis — Issues Found
CRITICAL
Hardcoded API URL in two places — api.ts:4 and authSlice.ts:4 both hardcode http://localhost:2000. This will break in any non-local environment. Should use process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL.

ForgotPasswordForm is a non-functional stub — components/ForgotPasswordForm/index.tsx renders a form with no state, no submission handler, and no API call. Users clicking "Send reset link" get nothing.


HIGH
Fire-and-forget notification promises — notify.ts:17: notifyUser() and notifyUsers() use .then().catch() chains that are never awaited or returned. Errors are silently logged to console only — callers have no way to know notifications failed.

clearAuth doesn't clear user state — authSlice.ts:108: The clearAuth reducer only sets checked: true but doesn't dispatch any action to clear the user from the userSlice. After a failed token refresh, the user object may remain stale in the store.

No error boundary pages — The frontend has no error.tsx files for any route. Any rendering crash shows the default Next.js error page instead of a graceful fallback.

Imperative navigation on auth failure — api.ts:23: Uses window.location.href = '/login' instead of Next.js router, causing a full page reload and losing client-side state.

formatTournament uses any type — tournamentController.ts:9: formatTournament(tournament: any) loses all type safety. The bracket manipulation code throughout the backend relies heavily on any.

Tournament creator null reference — tournamentController.ts:26: If a creator user is deleted from the DB, tournament.creator is null and the ternary handles it, but many other places access .creator properties directly without null checks.

MEDIUM
Inconsistent req.user null handling — The backend mixes req.user?.id (optional chaining) and req.user.id (direct access) across controllers. Routes using optionalAuth can crash if req.user is undefined.

Modal missing ARIA attributes — index.tsx:30: No role="dialog", aria-modal="true", or aria-labelledby on the modal container.

Silent error swallowing — 15+ locations across the frontend use catch { } or .catch(() => {}) to silently swallow errors, making debugging difficult and hiding failures from users.

Message sender impersonation risk — The Message model allows sender_id: null with arbitrary sender_name. There's no type/role field to distinguish system messages from user messages, so a malicious API call could fake system notifications.

Duplicate API_URL definitions — The auth slice (authSlice.ts:4) defines its own API_URL instead of importing from api.ts:4, making it easy for them to drift apart.

No route parameter validation — Frontend pages like app/teams/[id]/page.tsx and app/profile/[username]/page.tsx don't validate dynamic params before making API calls.

No request validation library — All backend controllers manually parse and validate request bodies/query params. Using zod or similar would reduce boilerplate and catch edge cases.

LOW
Lint errors in register page — app/register/page.tsx has ~14 eslint violations (import order and line length).

Weak frontend validation — page.tsx:28: Registration only checks password match — no strength requirements, no email format check, no min/max lengths.

useDebouncedSearch missing dependency — useDebouncedSearch.ts:16: buildUrl excluded from effect dependencies with a comment asking callers to pass a stable reference. If they don't, the debounce uses a stale function.

Performance — Skip-based pagination in controllers/userController.ts will degrade on large datasets. Cursor-based pagination would be more efficient.

JSON bracket data has no schema validation — The Prisma Json? type for bracket_data and team_assignments accepts any structure. Invalid data could corrupt tournament state with no validation layer.





